Hear Ye, Hear Ye! Year Books will be available soon!

We certainly cannot forget what a memorable school year 2019-20 has been! We will be offering year books for $8. However, we need your help! In order to know how many to order we ask that you email Mrs. McCloud the number of year books you would like to purchase (brenda.mccloud@ogden.k12.ia.us).

More information will come with dates and times they will be available to be picked up.

New this year! When picking up your book, you have the option to put your name into a drawing for a fun "summer package" sponsored by our very own PTO. All proceeds from our year book sales go back to the students/school.

Have a wonderful Memorial Day Weekend!

post_text: Dear Families: We are aware of the Governor's announcement today that schools will remain closed for the remainder of the school year. This news does not change the plans teachers have in place for the next two weeks. Expect an update next week from your teachers and principal about next steps. We will address all topics mentioned today by the governor, including future learning options, technology for all students, cleaning out lockers/desks, and how we support our Ogden return to learning plan. Our team is working quickly so that we can communicate the next steps for Ogden CSD students. Thank you for your continued partnership with our school district.
text: Dear Families: We are aware of the Governor's announcement today that schools will remain closed for the remainder of the school year. This news does not change the plans teachers have in place for the next two weeks. Expect an update next week from your teachers and principal about next steps. We will address all topics mentioned today by the governor, including future learning options, technology for all students, cleaning out lockers/desks, and how we support our Ogden return to learning plan. Our team is working quickly so that we can communicate the next steps for Ogden CSD students. Thank you for your continued partnership with our school district.

post_text:
Take the Challenge!
The Kids Heart Challenge is a fun and exciting event where your student learns about their heart while helping others by raising money for the American Heart Association. It prepares your child for success through physical and emotional well-being.

Ogden Elementary will kick off our Heart Challenge on Tuesday (2/11). Help your children go online at heart.org/kidsheartchallenge or download the Kids Heart Challenge mobile app to make a pledge to be more heart healthy and earn a free powerband. Our goal is to have 100% of our students take their heart healthy challenge online to move more, be kind, or be prepared! When your child takes their challenge, they will become a Heart Hero!

post_text: 5th graders have been learning about Veteran's Day and yesterday received a visit from Mrs. Savits and her sister, Bev. They shared memories from their father O.J. Thompson, who served as a 2nd Lieutenant in the U.S. Army during WWII with the 96th Infantry Division in the South Pacific on the Islands of Leyte and Okinawa. He was a recipient of the Purple Heart and Bronze Star medals and in 2001 his unit was awarded the Presidential Unit Citation for valor.

post_text: Last week during Fire Safety Prevention Week volunteers from the Ogden Fire Department stopped by to give instruction to the students on fire safety and planning escape routes. They were able to see the truck's equipment and sit in a fire truck. Thank you to our local volunteers for spending their afternoon with us!

post_text:
There has been lots of counting and estimating happening in Mrs. Germer's 2nd Grade Enrichment group. We are doing an ABC's of Corn unit, where kids explore corn, its attributes, growing patterns, and relevance to our world!
In these photos the students are seeing if there are 16 rows and approximately 800 kernels of corn on an ear.

post_text: The 4th graders went on a field trip this week (originally Swede Point Park in Madrid but moved to Boone County Fairgrounds due to weather). The kids learned (Ag in the Classroom) all about watersheds, they were shown a rainfall simulator, and were able to play a game at the Prairie Station.

post_text: This week all three kindergarten classes were able to meet with their 5th grade science buddies to do an experiment. They worked together to build a strong boat out of a piece of aluminum foil that could hold pennies without sinking in a tub of water. A big thank you to Mrs. Kruse and her 5th grade students for this fun experiment!
